        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Mercantile Liby. Dec. 13. 1882<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr. Morais&#44; Dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>I thought that<lb/> I would see what our wise men would<lb/> do in the way of justifying their state&#45;<lb/>ments in regard to Rev. Samuel M. Isaacs.<lb/>  I am a Temperance man&#44; but strongly<lb/> opposed to all endeavors to promote the<lb/> good cause by that which is false.  The<lb/> late Mr. Isaacs was&#44; I doubt not&#44; a<lb/> very conscientious man&#44; and he must<lb/> have known well the usages of his peo<lb/>ple.  He could&#44; therefore&#44; never have said<lb/> what is attributed to him.<lb/></p>
            <p>In the second paragraph of this little<lb/> article I have made a comprehensive as<lb/>sertion&#44; which I suppose&#44; is undeniable.  I suppose<lb/> that I can stand by this confidently.  If anyone<lb/> can successfully contradict this&#44; please to let<lb/> me know it.  You observe that it covers the<lb/> <hi rend="underline">past</hi>&#44; as well as the <hi rend="underline">present</hi>.  Is this right&#63;  I am<lb/> desirous of holding the <hi rend="underline">impregnable truth</hi>.  You<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>are aware that these inquiries do not<lb/> arise from any <hi rend="underline">meddling</hi> with the affairs<lb/> of your people&#44; but from the use which one<lb/> zealous Temp. writers are meeting &#40;falsely&#44;<lb/> as I suppose&#41; of your usages.<lb/></p>
            <p>Am I not correct if I say&#45;&#45;&#40;as I have<lb/> said in print&#44;&#41; that in the Mishna those<lb/> who search the house in order to remove&#44;<lb/> at the proper time&#44; all leavened articles&#44;<lb/> are instructed to look <hi rend="underline">between the casks<lb/> of wine</hi>&#44; to see if any leavened thing has<lb/> <sic>accidently</sic> been left there&#59; and does not<lb/> this imply&#44; unquestionably&#44; that the casks<lb/> of wine are <hi rend="underline">not</hi> to be removed&#63;  Is not<lb/> this <hi rend="underline">derisive</hi>&#8212;so far as the Mishna is<lb/> concerned&#63;  I am sure I cannot see<lb/> why it is not.  And further&#8212;is it not ex<lb/>plicitly declared&#44; in some of your standards&#44;<lb/> that the juices of fruits <hi rend="underline">do not ferment</hi><lb/> i. e. in such manner as to give rise to a<lb/> principle which is to be accounted as<lb/> <hi rend="underline">leaven</hi>&#63;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>The editor of the &#34;<hi rend="underline">Jewish Messenger</hi>&#34;<lb/> writes to me that he considers the<lb/> statement attributed to his father as<lb/> wholly apocryphal.<lb/></p>
            <p>I am resolved to fight &#40;&#33;&#41; our<lb/> Temp. men when they set up any false<lb/> pretenses&#59; and I must&#44; of course&#44; try<lb/> to be sure of my own ground.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>The &#34;Congregationalist&#34; &#40;Boston&#41; is<lb/> conducted by Rev. Dr. Dexter&#44; an able<lb/> and studious man&#44; who sympathies<lb/> strongly with me in my views and<lb/> aims in this discussion&#44; and who is<lb/> also a decided Temp. man.<lb/></p>
            <p>I thank you for the kindness with<lb/> which you have formerly replied to va<lb/>rious inquiries&#59; and if now you see me<lb/> <hi rend="underline">at all</hi> on doubtful ground&#44; I will deem<lb/> it a great favor if you will set me right.<lb/></p>
            <p>I am&#44; with great respect&#44;<lb/>
                Philada.		Yours&#44; S. C. Brace.<lb/></p>
        </body>
